00:12:49.583 --> 00:12:52.845
- Okay, so we'll go to questions
from the second session,

00:12:52.845 --> 00:12:55.087
a question for David Haig.

00:12:55.087 --> 00:12:56.957
It's a bit complex, but I think

00:12:56.957 --> 00:12:59.057
there's some interesting stuff in here.

00:12:59.057 --> 00:13:01.959
For offsprings with defects
passed on maternally,

00:13:01.959 --> 00:13:04.642
daughters may not suffer,
but will pass on genes

00:13:04.642 --> 00:13:07.566
to their sons who exhibit defects.

00:13:07.566 --> 00:13:10.319
Will defects in sons be
less in the first born

00:13:10.319 --> 00:13:12.986
and more in the subsequent sons?

00:13:18.513 --> 00:13:22.430
- There are a lot of
difficult questions there.

00:13:26.871 --> 00:13:30.893
First of all, the genetic
defects we're looking at,

00:13:30.893 --> 00:13:34.794
you know, those are the
mutations that Randy talked about

00:13:34.794 --> 00:13:38.544
that just happen that
are bad and maladaptive,

00:13:38.544 --> 00:13:43.106
but they provide information
about what the genes

00:13:43.106 --> 00:13:47.715
that aren't working do
during normal development,

00:13:47.715 --> 00:13:50.324
so I wouldn't want to
suggest that any of these

00:13:50.324 --> 00:13:53.991
defect conditions are
adaptive in any sense.

00:13:55.889 --> 00:13:57.889
Since I have the podium,

00:13:59.522 --> 00:14:04.407
I want to put something out
there fascinating for you.

00:14:04.407 --> 00:14:07.881
We now know that during
pregnancy, that once a woman

00:14:07.881 --> 00:14:11.609
has been pregnant, cells
from each of her offspring

00:14:11.609 --> 00:14:15.230
colonize her body and persist in her body

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:17.318
for the rest of her life.

00:14:17.318 --> 00:14:19.434
And we also know that
there are populations

00:14:19.434 --> 00:14:23.577
of maternal cells that
colonize in offspring bodies

00:14:23.577 --> 00:14:27.744
and remain in those bodies,
often for the rest of the life.

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:33.910
During pregnancy, a mother's
mother's cells increase

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:37.383
in frequency in her blood,
and so there's a possibility

00:14:37.383 --> 00:14:41.621
that maternal grandmother
cells can colonize a fetus.

00:14:41.621 --> 00:14:44.477
And since cells from previous pregnancies

00:14:44.477 --> 00:14:47.577
are in the mother's body,
there's a possibility

00:14:47.577 --> 00:14:52.113
that cells of older siblings
can move across the placenta

00:14:52.113 --> 00:14:56.113
and move into younger
siblings, so these are all

00:14:57.282 --> 00:15:00.185
anecdotal observations that are out there,

00:15:00.185 --> 00:15:02.541
but I think it raises the
possibility of all sorts

00:15:02.541 --> 00:15:05.847
of really, things that
we haven't thought about

00:15:05.847 --> 00:15:09.984
of effects within families
if sometimes cells

00:15:09.984 --> 00:15:12.908
from the genetic
individual of our siblings

00:15:12.908 --> 00:15:16.575
can be colonizing our
own bodies, thank you.

00:15:17.678 --> 00:15:19.292
- Question for Cynthia Beall.

00:15:19.292 --> 00:15:23.869
Does the difference between
the Andeans and the Tibetans

00:15:23.869 --> 00:15:27.165
reflect the time in
which they have adapted,

00:15:27.165 --> 00:15:31.982
or is it the environment
in which they have adapted?

00:15:31.982 --> 00:15:34.974
- That's a very good question to which

00:15:34.974 --> 00:15:36.651
I don't know the answer.

00:15:36.651 --> 00:15:40.818
I would add a third option to
the time and the environment

00:15:43.013 --> 00:15:45.680
and that is evolutionary history

00:15:46.832 --> 00:15:49.723
and micro-evolutionary history.

00:15:49.723 --> 00:15:52.442
It is the case that
someone has been living

00:15:52.442 --> 00:15:56.002
on the Tibetan plateau for much longer

00:15:56.002 --> 00:15:59.810
than someone has been
living on the Andean plateau

00:15:59.810 --> 00:16:03.810
so it's possible that
given another 15,000 years

00:16:05.661 --> 00:16:09.828
Andean highlanders might converge
upon the Tibetan phenotype

00:16:13.868 --> 00:16:18.026
The fact that we see signals of selection

00:16:18.026 --> 00:16:21.323
that are different in the two populations

00:16:21.323 --> 00:16:25.352
suggests that that is not going to happen.

00:16:25.352 --> 00:16:28.729
The questions about
differences in environment

00:16:28.729 --> 00:16:33.662
is an interesting one because
I think what you're doing

00:16:33.662 --> 00:16:37.867
is implicitly asking well,
you're focusing on high-altitudes

00:16:37.867 --> 00:16:40.756
and you're focusing on
hypoxia, but what about

00:16:40.756 --> 00:16:45.100
could dietary differences,
could latitudinal differences

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:47.085
and ultraviolet radiation differences

00:16:47.085 --> 00:16:50.762
and infectious disease
differences contribute

00:16:50.762 --> 00:16:54.666
to the pattern of differences,
and the answer is yes,

00:16:54.666 --> 00:16:58.250
it's possible, we don't have any evidence.

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:01.750
The third option that I introduced is that

00:17:03.766 --> 00:17:07.933
the population that gave rise
to the Tibetan population

00:17:09.238 --> 00:17:13.321
came from northern eastern
Asia, and that is also

00:17:14.333 --> 00:17:18.500
the population that gave
rise to the Native Americans.

00:17:20.634 --> 00:17:25.257
And so it's possible that
in the course of moving

00:17:25.257 --> 00:17:28.298
from the Old World to the New World,

00:17:28.298 --> 00:17:31.656
there was genetic drift,
there were new mutations,

00:17:31.656 --> 00:17:34.509
there were adaptations to
other environmental factors

00:17:34.509 --> 00:17:39.385
along the way so that the
genome, the details of the genome

00:17:39.385 --> 00:17:42.314
that the Andean highlanders
took to altitude

00:17:42.314 --> 00:17:44.656
were different than that for Tibetans

00:17:44.656 --> 00:17:48.920
and that would be a great
question to sort out.

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:50.925
And if the person who
asked that is looking for

00:17:50.925 --> 00:17:53.738
a dissertation topic, go for it.

00:17:53.738 --> 00:17:55.988
(applause)

00:17:59.624 --> 00:18:01.482
- Okay, so I think Charlie Nunn

00:18:01.482 --> 00:18:05.267
takes the prize for the
maximum number of questions.

00:18:05.267 --> 00:18:07.845
Sleep, everybody's interested in sleep,

00:18:07.845 --> 00:18:10.120
but we can't really go
through all the questions,

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:13.847
but I'll give a sort
of a combined question.

00:18:13.847 --> 00:18:15.949
One question which has two flip sides,

00:18:15.949 --> 00:18:19.896
one is you highlighted the
risk of short fragmented sleep,

00:18:19.896 --> 00:18:22.694
but what about sleeping too much,

00:18:22.694 --> 00:18:25.805
either because of sleeping
too much because you're lazy

00:18:25.805 --> 00:18:29.345
or because you get some drugs,
could that have an effect

00:18:29.345 --> 00:18:33.211
on cognitive deficits
and on the other hand,

00:18:33.211 --> 00:18:35.099
do the requirements of modern life

00:18:35.099 --> 00:18:39.010
which are very different from
the hunter-gatherer lifestyle

00:18:39.010 --> 00:18:42.343
actually require you to have more sleep?

00:18:43.662 --> 00:18:45.830
- [Charles] I'm sorry,
say the second one again.

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:49.997
- The second one is given
the stresses and environment

00:18:50.997 --> 00:18:55.017
of modern life, could
it be that you actually

00:18:55.017 --> 00:18:59.383
need more sleep now that
the hunter-gather needs.

00:18:59.383 --> 00:19:00.869
- Yeah, okay.

00:19:00.869 --> 00:19:03.493
Well these are really
interesting questions

00:19:03.493 --> 00:19:05.415
and clearly there's a lot
that we still don't know

00:19:05.415 --> 00:19:09.351
about sleep and it's effects on health.

00:19:09.351 --> 00:19:10.885
The evidence that is out suggests

00:19:10.885 --> 00:19:15.380
that there's sort of a sweet
spot of around eight hours,

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:18.793
there's probably a lot of error on that

00:19:18.793 --> 00:19:21.819
and that sleeping too
little or sleeping too much

00:19:21.819 --> 00:19:26.584
will have health consequences,
negative health consequences

00:19:26.584 --> 00:19:30.755
and so it probably is the
case that sleeping too much

00:19:30.755 --> 00:19:35.234
would also contribute to some
negative health consequences.

00:19:35.234 --> 00:19:38.579
Now I don't know a lot about
that side of the equation,

00:19:38.579 --> 00:19:42.145
I think most people are
focusing on the other side

00:19:42.145 --> 00:19:44.943
in terms of too little sleep.

00:19:44.943 --> 00:19:47.474
It's also interesting
to think about whether

00:19:47.474 --> 00:19:49.343
the stresses of modern life would lead us

00:19:49.343 --> 00:19:50.926
to need more sleep.

00:19:53.559 --> 00:19:55.416
I can't say that's really

00:19:55.416 --> 00:19:58.545
come up in a lot of our conversations.

00:19:58.545 --> 00:20:01.349
The people we study in
Madagascar and I go to Madagascar

00:20:01.349 --> 00:20:04.811
with David, I've not yet
been to see the Hadza,

00:20:04.811 --> 00:20:06.424
but when we got to Madagascar,

00:20:06.424 --> 00:20:08.924
those people are working really hard.

00:20:08.924 --> 00:20:12.546
We're of course, often
there in the harvest season

00:20:12.546 --> 00:20:16.946
and their activity levels
are incredibly high.

00:20:16.946 --> 00:20:20.215
We actually had the hypothesis
that they might sleep

00:20:20.215 --> 00:20:24.166
more than eight hours because
they don't have electricity

00:20:24.166 --> 00:20:26.332
and I think that there'd
be an argument to say

00:20:26.332 --> 00:20:29.990
that they should sleep more
than a typical westerner

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:32.040
does just because of all
the physical activity

00:20:32.040 --> 00:20:35.365
that they're undertaking,
hauling firewood,

00:20:35.365 --> 00:20:39.220
hauling water, you know,
harvesting these crops,

00:20:39.220 --> 00:20:42.152
bringing the crops in,
they're really working hard

00:20:42.152 --> 00:20:44.595
so I would actually expect
them to need more sleep

00:20:44.595 --> 00:20:47.637
than a typical westerner,
but I think these are

00:20:47.637 --> 00:20:49.715
really interesting questions

00:20:49.715 --> 00:20:52.663
that we don't yet have answers to them,

00:20:52.663 --> 00:20:55.788
so very nice questions, thank you.

00:20:55.788 --> 00:20:57.560
